%% Diagram: How JVM stop-the-world GC pauses inflate Cassandra P99 read latency
%% Type: sequence
%%{init: {'htmlLabels': false}}%%
sequenceDiagram
    autonumber
    participant Cli as Client
    participant Coord as Cassandra coordinator (JVM)
    participant Mut as Mutator threads
    participant GC as JVM GC (stop-the-world)
    participant Disk as SSTable / page cache

    Note over Coord,Mut: Steady state — typical read ~5 ms
    Cli->>Coord: read(key)
    Coord->>Mut: schedule read task
    Mut->>Disk: fetch row from memtable + SSTable
    Disk-->>Mut: row bytes
    Mut-->>Coord: response
    Coord-->>Cli: 5 ms (avg case)

    Note over Mut,GC: Eden fills from row + iterator + buffer allocations
    GC->>Coord: STW Young GC begins
    Note over Coord,Mut: All mutator threads paused for tens of ms
    Cli->>Coord: read(key) (queued)
    Cli->>Coord: read(key) (queued)
    Cli->>Coord: read(key) (queued)
    GC-->>Coord: STW Young GC ends

    Note over Coord,Cli: Backlog drains — every queued read inherits the pause
    Coord-->>Cli: 25-60 ms (P99 spike)
    Coord-->>Cli: 25-60 ms (P99 spike)
    Coord-->>Cli: 25-60 ms (P99 spike)

    Note over GC,Disk: GC stalls consumed 1.25 % of wall time at low traffic, 2.5 % at peak<br/>→ dominant source of P99 variance, independent of disk or network
